Rating: 4
Fantastic soup. I recently ate this soup at a Moroccan restaurant in Paris and wanted to recreate it. This recipe nearly blew me away. I followed it exactly. The only change I made was to use potatoes instead of the turnips.

Rating: 4
Fantastic vegetarian food! Don't let the complex sounding nature of it scare you away--I do not cook the couscous their way, but instead use whole wheat and cook it like the box suggests. This is a favorite and I have made this numerous times--my family as well as guests. Version of Ras Al Hout that I use: 1 tsp cumin, 1 tsp ginger, 1 tsp turmeric, 1 tsp salt, 3/4 tsp cinnamon, 3/4 tsp cardamon, 3/4 tsp black pepper, 1/2 tsp White pepper, 1/2 tsp coriander, 1/2 tsp nutmeg

Rating: 3
i did the best i could with this recipe - i couldn't find the ras-el-hanout or the harissa, so i found recipes online (see my other post) and tried to create them. i have no idea how close to the true thing they are. likewise, i couldn't find barley couscous anywhere, so i used whole wheat couscous and cooked them the normal way. the verdict: a wonderfully different flavor. my partner absolutely loved it and said it was one of the best recipes she's had in a long time. i thought it was good, but maybe because of all the work i put into it, i'm not as in love with it as she is. next time it will be easier to make and i will rate it higher.

